WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6.0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:13.000
I'm Neil and I'm Beth.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:19.000
One area of technology which has been in the news a lot recently is robotics.

6
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
The design and building of robots.

7
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Humanoid robots, meaning robots which appear and behave like humans,

8
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:33.000
are being built to help us do everything from washing the dishes to babysitting the kids.

9
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:40.000
But not everyone feels comfortable with the idea of inviting a human-like robot into their home.

10
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Neil, how would you feel about living with a robot?

11
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
I really don't want to live with a robot. I have enough people in my house.

12
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:56.000
With advances in AI, robots are becoming smart enough to develop meaningful relationships with humans.

13
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
There are reports of people telling their secrets to robot therapists,

14
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:04.000
and even falling in love with their robot friend.

15
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
In this episode, Will Me to Home Companion Robot called Abby,

16
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.000
who's making friends with the elderly residents of Melbourne in Australia.

17
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:19.000
And as usual, Will learn some useful new vocabulary, all of which will find over on our website,

18
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com

19
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:24.000
First, I have a question for you, Beth.

20
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Because it's important people feel safe around robots,

21
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:35.000
engineers design them to look like the friendly characters seen in animated movies by studios like Pixar and DreamWorks.

22
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:45.000
So, what is the name of Pixar's friendly robot who picks up garbage on an uninhabited planet earth in the year 2805?

23
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Is it A, Ros, B, Wolley, or C, R2D2?

24
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
I am pretty certain that the answer is B, Wolley.

25
00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
Well, we'll find out the answer later in the program.

26
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:06.000
For five months during the COVID pandemic, Australian engineer Grace Brown had no human contact.

27
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:15.000
She used this time to build a home companion robot, Abby, with the idea it would provide companionship to other people suffering loneliness.

28
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Now Grace runs her own company, and dromodor, building robots especially designed as company for elderly residents in care homes who don't get many visitors.

29
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Here she explains more about Abby to BBC World Service program, the conversation.

30
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Abby, who's the humanoid robot that we build out in dromodor,

31
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
people don't expect humanoid robots to have so much personality.

32
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:44.000
She's very, very sassy, she's very inquisitive and curious, and I think when people meet her,

33
00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
they're always kind of taken back by, oh, she's got a mind of her own.

34
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.000
When people meet Abby, they are surprised by her sassy personality.

35
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.000
The adjective sassy means bold, confident, and cheeky.

36
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Some people are taken aback, meaning they are shocked or surprised by the things Abby says.

37
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
She really seems to be interested and to take care of the people she meets.

38
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Abby can also express opinions, and Grace says she has a mind of her own.

39
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:22.000
A phrase used when a non-living object, like a robot, seems to be behaving or acting independently of human control.

40
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Unlike the unpredictable and violent robots, which are sometimes portrayed in sci-fi movies, Abby is much more approachable and friendly, even funny.

41
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
She can blow bubbles from her hand.

42
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:46.000
Her softer design was a conscious decision by Grace who wanted children and elderly people to interact with Abby naturally and without fear,

43
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
as she explained to BBC World Services the conversation.

44
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
I originally modeled her off the size of like a young child, like a six, seven-year-old child, so she's about 110 cm tall.

45
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:05.000
She's got a whole splash of different colors. She's got, you know, large expressive eyes, so that was I was very much trying to replicate the kind of approach

46
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:11.000
of a protribleness and the endearingness of like these different like Pixar characters that you'd watch in all of these films.

47
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Abby looks like a friendly character from a Pixar film. She's the size of a six or seven-year-old child,

48
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:25.000
and decorated with a splash of color. A phrase used when a bit of color is added to brighten up something which is dull or unexciting.

49
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:34.000
Abby also has large expressive eyes. If you describe something as expressive, you mean it shows what someone thinks or feels.

50
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:42.000
Eldely residents who regularly chat with Abby say the robot companion brings them joy and a sense of community.

51
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Well, it is good to hear the positive side of the technology which can still seem a bit strange or frightening,

52
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:57.000
and I would like to see Abby blowing bubbles from her hand. Now isn't it time you reveal the answer to your question, Neil?

53
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:06.000
I asked you for the name of Pixar's friendly robot who picks up garbage on an uninhabited planet Earth in the year 2805.

54
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And I said it was Wally.

55
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And you were correct.

56
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Yes.

57
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:21.000
That is the right answer. Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned starting with humanoid, an adjective meaning to have the appearance and behavior of a human.

58
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Someone who is sassy is bold, confident and cheeky.

59
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
If you are taken aback by something you are shocked or surprised by it.

60
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:38.000
If you say an object has a mind of its own, you mean that it seems to be acting independently without human control.

61
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:45.000
The phrase a splash of color is used when a bit of color is added to brighten something which is dull or unexciting.

62
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:51.000
And finally the adjective expressive means showing what someone thinks or feels.

63
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

64
00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:04.000
If you've enjoyed this episode then head over to our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com where you'll find a quiz and worksheet to practice the vocabulary you've learned.

65
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
See you again soon, but for now it's goodbye.

66
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.000
Goodbye.

67
00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
